
What this means

For AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity, AWS checks:
	•	the OIDC provider
	•	the role trust policy
	•	the token’s aud
	•	the token’s sub  ￼

If you still get the same token error after updating the workflow and role references, then one of these is true:

1. The new repo is producing a different token than you expect

GitHub OIDC tokens include claims that identify the workflow context, and aud/sub are commonly used in trust conditions. A different repo, branch, or workflow context can change those claims.  ￼

2. The IAM OIDC provider registration is not aligned

AWS requires the OIDC identity provider to be configured correctly, including the provider URL and allowed audience/client IDs. If that provider-level setup is wrong, role trust changes alone won’t fix it.  ￼

3. Your internal auth action is not requesting the audience you think it is

With your org’s custom GitHub Enterprise/internal action setup, the token audience may be controlled by the internal platform, not just by what you copied from the old repo.

⸻

The fastest way to prove where the mismatch is

Compare these between working repo and failing repo:

1. OIDC provider ARN
2. IAM role ARN
3. Exact trust relationship JSON
4. Exact workflow auth step
5. Exact error text
6. Actual token aud shown in logs
7. Actual token sub shown in logs, if your internal tooling exposes it

If even one of those differs, that is enough to break OIDC.

⸻

Very likely root cause now

Since you copied from a working repo and updated the obvious names, the most likely remaining issue is one of these:
	•	the OIDC provider audience/client ID list does not include what the new repo is using
	•	the actual token audience from the new repo is not the same as the old one
	•	the subject claim pattern for the new repo is not matched by trust
	•	the repo has not been onboarded in whatever central internal OIDC trust setup your company uses

⸻

What to ask your platform/IAM team

Send this:

I copied the working GitHub Actions OIDC setup from another repository and updated the repo-specific references, but the new repository still fails during AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity.
Please compare the working repo and new repo for:
	•	OIDC provider configuration
	•	allowed audience/client IDs on the provider
	•	role trust policy (aud and sub)
	•	whether the new repository is onboarded in the internal OIDC trust setup
The Dockerfile/workflow structure is the same; the failure appears to be at token trust validation.

⸻

One hard truth

If the working repo succeeds and the new repo fails with the same internal auth action pattern, then this is usually not a code problem anymore. It is an identity/trust setup problem.
